                "accept_rate": 75
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1344634673,
            "creation_date": 1344634673,
            "body": "<p>Being completely unaware of peer classes, i would do the following: Have a <code>native void register()<\/code> (or such) in your Java class which you want to pair. In C JNI part, store a <code>GlobalRef<\/code> of the calling <code>jobject<\/code> as a key in <code>std::map&lt;jobject,NativeImplementationObject&gt;<\/code>. You can set the <code>GlobalRef<\/code> key to the C++ object via constructor, to simplify callbacks to JVM. On any subsequent call from JVM to any sensor-related native methods, look up the right <code>NativeImplementationObject<\/code> by doing <code>IsSameObject<\/code> comparison with the current calling jobject. Then simply \"forward\" the call to that object. The JNI stub implementation will be just a thin dispatcher holding the map. There is of course nontrivial part of deleting all objects and global refs at appropriate time (no automagic JVM) but that's beyond what can be explained here.<\/p>\n\n<p>On a second thought, you may not need a map, unless the number of sensors will be moderately big (on the order of tens at least) or you are willing to learn some human skills by writing compare predicate function using the mentioned <code>IsSameObject<\/code>. A simple list of structs would do as well (for monkeys and humans alike).<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 11909605,
            "question_id": 11876501
        }
